T1  - Relational Pluralism Within and Between Organizations
AU  - Shipilov, Andrew
AU  - Gulati, Ranjay
AU  - Kilduff, Martin
AU  - Li, Stan
AU  - Tsai, Wenpin
Y1  - 2014/01/23
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2013.1145
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2013.1145
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 449
EP  - 459
VL  - 57
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Relational pluralism exists when actors maintain multiple kinds of relationships with one another and develop multiple identities as a result. The outcomes of relational pluralism can include greater flexibility in building network ties, more stable exchange relationships, and the ability to adopt tailored innovations. We develop a typology of relational pluralism and examine both the positive and negative features of relational pluralism inside and across organizations. We conclude with a discussion of future directions for research.
AB  - Relational pluralism exists when actors maintain multiple kinds of relationships with one another and develop multiple identities as a result. The outcomes of relational pluralism can include greater flexibility in building network ties, more stable exchange relationships, and the ability to adopt tailored innovations. We develop a typology of relational pluralism and examine both the positive and negative features of relational pluralism inside and across organizations. We conclude with a discussion of future directions for research.
